\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order for a spacecraft to successfully land on the surface of a planet
 or other body in the correct location, accurate possition, attitude, and
 velocity data is required.
 There are many useful instruments which contribute to this data.
 Doppler ladar in particular is interesting because it can contribute to
 each aspect of the aforementioned data.
 If used correctly the measurements of a multi-beam Doppler ladar system
 can be combined to get an accurate velocity vector, attitude, and if enough
 beams or beam steering angles are available Doppler ladar can even be used
 to aquire necessary navigational information.
 A significant challenge in the design of any space craft is budgeting not
 only cost but also power, space, and weight.
 In order to maintain these budgets it is prudent to design or purchase
 a Doppler ladar system which reaches the performance requirements for the
 mission with minimum cost, power consumption, size, and weight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An individual or group tasked with purchasing or especially designing a
 Doppler ladar system would need to determine what kind of parameters in
 the system would meet the requirements of the mission.
 Evaluating the performance of a Doppler ladar system requires that either
 the system is built and tested experimentally or the system to be simulated.
 The problems with building a system and testing experimentally to determine
 if it meets mission requirements are obvious, if the system does not meet
 requirements large amounts of time and money have been wasted and if the
 system does meet requirements it is unknown whether a less expensive, smaller,
 or lower power system may have also met the requirements.
 Robust parameterized simulation tools for Doppler ladar, however, are not
 widely available and it would be time consuming and costly to create simulation
 tools to design one Doppler ladar system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
LadarSIM is a robust parameterized simulation tool for time of flight ladar
 developed at Utah State University's Center for Advanced Imaging and Ladar
 over the past decade and a half.
 LadarSIM has the flexibility to simulate a wide range of time of flight
 ladar systems with varrying beam and scanner patterns with paramterized
 transmitters and receivers.
 These simulated systems can be evaluated using scenarios consisting of
 user specified terrain, targets, and flight paths.
 Taking full advantage of the significant work that has gone into creating
 the LadarSIM software, a simulation of a paramterized Doppler transmitter
 and receiver will be added to LadarSIM to evaluate the performance of Doppler
 lidar systems.
 Utilizing this Doppler ladar simulation capability of LadarSIM a trade-off
 study will be perfomed to determine the effect of varrying laser transmission
 power, beam divergance, aperture diameter, and FFT size on a Doppler ladar
 system.
 These parameters have been selected becuase of the significant effect they
 can have on the performance, cost, size, and power consumption of a Doppler
 ladar system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is anticiapted that the results of this research will present a clear
 demonstration of the effects of these parameters on a Doppler ladar system.
 For each of these parameters it is expected that performance will increase
 as the value of the parameter is improved but diminishing returns will
 be evident.
 Using this data a designer would have strong guidence in designing the
 parameters of a Doppler ladar system to their mission requirements while
 expending the minimal necessary resources.
 
\end_layout

