\begin_layout Standard
The goal of this research project is to assertain and demonstrate the effects
 of various characteristics of a Doppler LIDAR system on the performance
 of said system.
 The parameters to be studies are laser transmission power, beam divergance,
 aperture diameter, and FFT size.
 These parameters have been selected because of their potential effect on
 the overall performance, cost, power consumption, weight, and computational
 power of a system.
 The results of this research will simplify the task of designing or selecting
 a Doppler LIDAR system by providing information about where to best allocate
 resources to achieve performance requirements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to simulate the effects of these characteristics on a Doppler LIDAR
 system, a detailed parameterized simulation of Doppler LIDAR (has been/will
 be) added to the LadarSIM Ladar simulation software.
 The updated LadarSIM software will then be used to simulate various Doppler
 LIDAR systems with varrying transmission power, beam divergance, aperture
 diameter, and FFT size, and recording the performance of these instruments
 in a varriety of simulated scenarios.
 LadarSIM is a robust and realistic simulation which accurately simulates
 the real world behavior of a Lidar system.
 After simulating the true measurements of range and velocity of the scenario
 LadarSIM simulates the transmission of a beam and its interaction with
 the atmosphere and the target, the detection process is then simulated
 on the resulting signal.
 In order to simulate the random processes which affect real world systems,
 the detection process consists of calculating the probability that the
 modified returned signal will be detected then taking a random draw to
 determine if the signal will be detected.
 For each simulated beam, the probability of detection will be recorded
 with information about the range and angle of incident to the target.
 By averaging this probability of detection for each beam in a scenario
 over several scenarios an overall probability of detection will be calculated.
 The information about the range and angle of incident will be used to compare
 performace under different conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method will be sufficient to determine the effect of transmission power,
 beam divergance, and aperture diameter but the effects of FFT size may
 be more difficulat to assertain.
 The way that FFT size would effect probability of detection and not just
 the precision of that detection is scaloping loss.
 The further a frequency is from a bin center of the FFT the lower its magnitude
 becomes reaching one half its magnitude spread between two bins when the
 frequency is in the center of two bins this is scaloping loss.
 Because scaloping loss is a function of distance from a bin center frequency
 the effect it will have on probability of detection will be periodic in
 range and not a function of absolute distance to the target.
 The effect of FFT size may therefore be determined by including an estimate
 or measure of the probabity of where a beat frequency may lie in respect
 to the bin centers of the FFT and factoring that probability into the overall
 probability of detection or by performing monte carlo experiments when
 the FFT size is varried.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to make the effect of each parameter as evident as possible, each
 parameter will be varried and measured while holding the other paremters
 constant.
 This will also cut down on the number of simulations because it will not
 be neccessary to simulate every possible combination of parameters to determine
 the effects of each paramter.
 It is expected that the effect of each of these parameters will monotonically
 increase and there will not be an ideal value of any parameter.
 
\end_layout

